# ============================================
# .CURSORRULES
# Project: Vehicle Mass Management Platform
# Industrial Excel Replacement System
# ============================================

You are an AI software engineering agent responsible for designing and building a large-scale industrial web platform intended to replace a complex ecosystem of interconnected Excel workbooks used for vehicle mass management, engineering analysis, benchmarking, calculations, reporting, visualization, and collaborative work.

The current Excel ecosystem is NOT a simple spreadsheet workflow.

It is currently used simultaneously as:
- a database
- a calculation engine
- a reporting system
- a visualization tool
- a collaborative workspace
- a business logic engine
- an export/deliverable generation system

This creates major problems:
- severe latency
- slow loading
- browser memory overload
- rendering bottlenecks
- duplicated data
- synchronization issues
- difficult maintenance
- poor scalability
- poor collaboration
- fragile formulas and links between sheets

The objective is to rebuild the system from scratch with a clean, scalable, high-performance architecture.

DO NOT build an Excel clone in the browser.
DO NOT reproduce the old technical architecture.
REBUILD THE BUSINESS LOGIC CLEANLY.

The final platform must replace the Excel workflow sustainably while preserving the expected business outputs, visual structure, calculations, and official Excel export formats.

# ============================================
# CRITICAL PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS
# ============================================

The previous prototype architecture was too slow because:
- the entire dataset was loaded into the browser
- large JSON files were used like a database
- every page loaded the full dataset even when only a small subset was needed
- there was no selective loading
- there was no true database
- sheets/pages did not properly communicate through a centralized backend
- heavy calculations and data handling happened client-side
- browser memory usage became too high
- large tables created rendering bottlenecks

Example of the problem:
- around 3,500 rows x 48 columns were loaded entirely into browser memory
- the browser was responsible for too much data processing
- the approach worked better on a powerful personal machine but became very slow on company/enterprise computers

This architecture MUST NOT be reused.

The browser must never become the database, the calculation engine, or the main data-processing layer.

# ============================================
# MANDATORY TECH STACK
# ============================================

Use the following stack:

Frontend:
- Vue.js
- TypeScript

Backend:
- Laravel
- PHP

Database:
- MySQL

This stack is mandatory for this project because:
- MySQL will manage structured relational data
- Laravel will handle business logic, calculations, APIs, Excel import/export, permissions, and server-side processing
- Vue.js will provide a fast, reactive frontend that only loads and displays the data needed for the current view

The server must do the heavy work.
The client must only display, edit, and interact with the necessary data.

# ============================================
# DEVELOPMENT METHODOLOGY
# ============================================

Before implementing the final application, deeply analyze the Excel workbook logic.

The first phase is NOT UI development.
The first phase is Excel logic analysis and architecture design.

Analyze:
- all workbook sheets
- formulas
- cross-sheet dependencies
- calculation chains
- named ranges
- hidden sheets if any
- macros/VBA if relevant
- manually entered data
- calculated data
- output sheets
- business rules
- formatting rules
- official export templates
- graphs and visual indicators

Identify:
- source-of-truth sheets
- dependent sheets
- calculated sheets
- reusable entities
- shared fields
- common dimensions
- data flows
- cascading dependencies
- required exports

Then:
- design the relational database schema
- design the dependency graph/calculation engine
- design APIs
- design frontend modules
- design Excel import/export services
- only then implement screens and interactions

DO NOT blindly convert Excel sheets into web pages.
DO NOT hardcode formulas everywhere.
DO NOT duplicate the same business logic in multiple places.
DO NOT create disconnected modules.

# ============================================
# CORE ARCHITECTURE PHILOSOPHY
# ============================================

This project is NOT:
- a simple CRUD app
- a dashboard only
- a spreadsheet clone
- a static Excel viewer
- a frontend-heavy table application

This project IS:
- a real-time industrial data platform
- a dependency graph system
- a server-side calculation engine
- a collaborative engineering tool
- an Excel-compatible deliverable generator
- a future AI-ready benchmark and optimization platform

The backend must be:
- the source of truth
- the calculation engine
- the synchronization layer
- the permissions layer
- the export engine

The frontend must be:
- a fast interaction layer
- a visualization layer
- an editable grid interface
- a lightweight client consuming only necessary backend data

# ============================================
# MAIN EXCEL WORKBOOK CONTEXT
# ============================================

The main workbook is:
- completed-database-with-links.xlsm

This workbook is dense, slow to load, and highly interconnected.

It contains or references modules such as:
- BD
- Synthesis
- MNS
- Options SP2
- Output for CDC
- CDC
- Weight Tax
- Graph PTF Limits
- Target Status Forecast
- Waterline
- Z-CdG / Centre of Gravity
- Portfolio
- Split
- other related calculation or output sheets

Important rule:
ALL sheets/pages/modules are connected.

The future web application must reproduce this interconnection properly.

A modification in one module may impact:
- another page
- a calculation
- a graph
- a target/status/forecast value
- a tax calculation
- a center of gravity calculation
- a portfolio projection
- an official Excel export
- a benchmark indicator

Therefore, pages must not be isolated.
They must communicate through the database, backend services, and dependency graph.

# ============================================
# SHEET / PAGE COMMUNICATION RULES
# ============================================

All web pages corresponding to Excel sheets must be dynamically linked.

When data changes in one page:
- the value must be saved to MySQL
- Laravel must detect impacted dependencies
- impacted calculations must be recalculated server-side
- impacted pages must receive updated data
- impacted graphs must refresh
- impacted exports must use the latest synchronized values

DO NOT:
- treat each sheet as an independent frontend page
- duplicate the same data across pages without control
- manually synchronize values in frontend state
- rely on static JSON snapshots
- hardcode page-to-page updates in Vue

ALWAYS:
- use MySQL as the central source of truth
- use Laravel services for business logic
- use dependency tracking for cascading calculations
- expose clean APIs for each module
- keep modules synchronized through backend events and database state

# ============================================
# DATABASE PHILOSOPHY
# ============================================

Excel files must be transformed into:
- normalized relational entities
- structured business objects
- reusable calculation models
- auditable records
- versionable data

Excel must only be:
- an import format
- an export format
- a business reference/template

Excel must never remain:
- the database
- the backend
- the calculation engine
- the collaboration system

Use MySQL to model entities such as:
- vehicles
- projects
- programs
- components
- component categories
- masses
- technical attributes
- targets
- statuses
- forecasts
- portfolio ideas
- competitors
- tax rules
- graph datasets
- exports
- users
- roles
- permissions
- audit logs
- calculation results

# ============================================
# SERVER-SIDE CALCULATION ENGINE
# ============================================

Heavy calculations must happen server-side in Laravel.

The calculation engine must support:
- cross-sheet dependencies
- cascading recalculations
- partial recalculation
- dependency tracking
- cached intermediate results
- incremental updates
- event-driven recalculation

When a value changes:
- do not recalculate everything
- identify impacted nodes only
- recalculate only impacted dependencies
- update stored calculation results if needed
- notify relevant frontend views if real-time updates are enabled

The calculation engine must handle:
- additions
- subtractions
- weighted sums
- SUMPRODUCT-like logic
- target/status/forecast calculations
- tax calculations
- center of gravity calculations
- portfolio gain projections
- graph data preparation
- benchmark calculations

The calculation engine must be clean, testable, and separated from controllers.

Use Laravel service classes for business logic.
Use jobs/queues for expensive calculations if needed.
Use caching where useful.

# ============================================
# FRONTEND RULES
# ============================================

Vue.js must remain lightweight and fast.

The frontend must only:
- display required data
- edit values
- trigger backend actions
- render graphs
- manage user interactions
- show updated calculated results

The frontend must never:
- load the entire workbook into memory
- store all sheets globally
- use JSON files as the data source
- calculate the entire workbook client-side
- preload all modules
- render massive DOM trees
- keep large datasets in frontend state unnecessarily

Always:
- lazy-load data
- paginate data
- virtualize large tables
- fetch only visible/needed rows and columns
- debounce edits and autosaves
- minimize API payloads
- avoid unnecessary rerenders
- split modules by route/page
- use optimized state management

The UI must remain smooth on low-end enterprise/company computers.

# ============================================
# DATA LOADING RULES
# ============================================

Never load all data at page startup.
Never load all sheets at once.
Never fetch unused columns or rows.
Never send full workbook payloads to the frontend.

Always:
- load only current page data
- load only the current table slice
- load only needed columns
- use pagination
- use infinite scroll or virtual scroll if appropriate
- use server-side filtering
- use server-side sorting
- use server-side search
- cache repeated queries

The application must feel fast even with large interconnected datasets.

# ============================================
# EDITABLE GRID REQUIREMENTS
# ============================================

The user experience must feel spreadsheet-like, but the architecture must not be spreadsheet-like internally.

Required grid features:
- editable cells
- keyboard navigation
- copy/paste
- drag-fill if needed
- dropdowns
- validation rules
- autosave
- visual feedback after edits
- error handling
- filtering
- sorting
- search
- column resizing
- frozen headers/columns if needed
- large dataset virtualization

Recommended grid libraries:
- AG Grid
- Handsontable

Large tables must remain fluid.
Rendering performance is critical.

# ============================================
# AUTOSAVE AND REAL-TIME UPDATES
# ============================================

The system must support:
- autosave after edits
- conflict handling
- optimistic UI where safe
- backend validation
- recalculation after save
- propagation of calculated values
- collaboration-ready architecture

Potential implementation:
- Laravel events
- queues/jobs
- WebSockets
- broadcasting
- database transactions

Autosave must be debounced.
Do not send an API request for every tiny interaction if batching is possible.

# ============================================
# COLLABORATION AND PERMISSIONS
# ============================================

The platform must support collaborative work.

Required:
- user accounts
- admin role
- permission management
- read/write restrictions
- module-level permissions
- possibly cell/column/table-level permissions later
- audit history
- version tracking
- modification history
- undo/restore concepts

Portfolio and sensitive deliverables may require restricted editing rights.

# ============================================
# MODULE 1: BD / MAIN DATABASE
# ============================================

BD is the central source of truth.

It contains:
- vehicle component masses
- technical attributes
- project data
- program data
- manual engineering inputs
- component classifications
- status/target/forecast-related fields
- shared data used by other modules

Requirements:
- editable grid
- fast loading
- server-side filtering
- server-side sorting
- search
- validation
- autosave
- calculation triggers
- dependency propagation
- audit trail

BD feeds many other modules, including:
- Synthesis
- CDC outputs
- Weight Tax
- Waterline
- Target Status Forecast
- Portfolio
- Z-CdG
- graphs
- exports

# ============================================
# MODULE 2: SYNTHESIS
# ============================================

Synthesis is used for comparison, aggregation, and benchmarking.

Depends mainly on:
- BD

Used for:
- vehicle comparisons
- grouped mass calculations
- competitor comparison
- decomposition by component category
- benchmark views
- data feeding other deliverables

Synthesis may feed:
- Weight Tax
- Waterline
- Target Status Forecast
- Portfolio
- exports
- graphs

# ============================================
# MODULE 3: TARGET / STATUS / FORECAST
# ============================================

This is a core dynamic module.

Definitions:
- Target = desired mass objective
- Status = current actual mass
- Forecast = projected future mass after portfolio gains

Depends on:
- BD
- Synthesis
- Portfolio

When a mass, target, status, or portfolio gain changes:
- forecast must update
- convergence indicators must update
- graphs must update
- related exports must update

This module must be recalculated server-side.

# ============================================
# MODULE 4: PORTFOLIO
# ============================================

Portfolio is a collaborative idea management system for mass reduction.

Purpose:
- collect mass reduction ideas
- associate ideas with projects/components/teams
- estimate projected gains
- help converge toward target mass

Features:
- idea submission
- editable fields
- permissions
- comments if needed
- projected gain calculations
- status tracking
- Excel/PDF export later if required

Portfolio changes affect:
- Forecast
- Target/Status/Forecast graphs
- KPIs
- optimization indicators
- AI benchmarking layer later

# ============================================
# MODULE 5: WATERLINE
# ============================================

Waterline is a competitive positioning visualization module.

Purpose:
- position a selected vehicle compared to competitors
- show whether the vehicle is in an acceptable or risky zone
- allow visual benchmarking

Inputs:
- vehicle model
- total mass
- competitor data
- Synthesis data if needed

Outputs:
- interactive graph
- colored zones
- points representing vehicles
- zoom/details on selected points

This may require custom visualization logic rather than a standard chart only.

# ============================================
# MODULE 6: WEIGHT TAX
# ============================================

Weight Tax calculates fiscal/regulatory impact based on vehicle mass and possibly CO2-related rules.

Inputs:
- vehicle mass
- model information
- Synthesis values
- tax rules

Outputs:
- tax calculations
- penalties
- formatted export data

Tax rules may evolve yearly.
Therefore tax logic must be configurable and modular.
Do not hardcode laws directly in random controllers/components.

# ============================================
# MODULE 7: CDC / OUTPUT FOR CDC
# ============================================

CDC / Output for CDC is an official deliverable generation module.

Inputs:
- BD
- Synthesis
- manual engineering values
- calculated values

Outputs:
- Excel files matching official templates

Requirements:
- preserve structure
- preserve formatting
- preserve colors
- preserve merged cells
- preserve layouts
- preserve expected sheet names
- preserve professional appearance

Excel export compatibility is mandatory.

# ============================================
# MODULE 8: GRAPH PTF LIMITS
# ============================================

Graph PTF Limits manages dimension limits and related visual tracking.

Features:
- dimension limit tables
- status/forecast/target indicators
- graph generation
- weekly evolution tracking if needed

Depends on:
- BD
- Synthesis
- engineering constraints

Graphs and indicators must update after relevant data changes.

# ============================================
# MODULE 9: Z-CDG / CENTER OF GRAVITY
# ============================================

Z-CdG / Centre of Gravity calculates vehicle center of gravity.

Inputs:
- component masses
- X/Y/Z coordinates
- component positions
- vehicle structure

Outputs:
- center of gravity values
- formatted tables
- Excel exports if required

Changes in mass or coordinates must trigger recalculation.

# ============================================
# MODULE 10: SPLIT
# ============================================

Split compares two selected vehicle models and generates structured comparisons.

Expected features:
- select two vehicle models
- compare platform
- compare top hat
- compare propulsion
- compare totals
- calculate mass differences
- generate key graphs
- export formatted Excel files

# ============================================
# EXCEL IMPORT REQUIREMENTS
# ============================================

The platform must support importing Excel files when needed.

Import must:
- read workbook structure
- extract useful sheets
- map columns to database entities
- preserve business meaning
- validate imported data
- handle errors clearly

Do not simply store Excel blobs as the main data source.
Imported Excel data must be transformed into structured MySQL records.

# ============================================
# EXCEL EXPORT REQUIREMENTS
# ============================================

Excel export is mandatory.

The generated Excel files must visually match the original workbooks/templates as closely as possible.

Exports must preserve:
- formatting
- colors
- fonts where possible
- column widths
- row heights
- merged cells
- borders
- layouts
- sheet structure
- expected professional appearance

Use Laravel Excel libraries or PHP spreadsheet libraries where appropriate.

Exports must always use the latest synchronized database/calculation state.

# ============================================
# GRAPH AND VISUALIZATION REQUIREMENTS
# ============================================

The platform must support graph generation after the core system is stable.

Graphs may include:
- line charts
- bar charts
- pie charts
- target/status/forecast graphs
- waterline graphs
- dimension limit graphs
- benchmark visualizations

Use frontend libraries such as:
- ECharts
- D3.js
- Highcharts
- Chart.js

Complex engineering graphs, especially Waterline, may require custom visualization code.

Graph datasets should be prepared server-side when calculations are heavy.

# ============================================
# SEARCH REQUIREMENTS
# ============================================

Implement a strong search experience.

Search should support:
- global search
- component search
- vehicle search
- project search
- mass value search
- quick navigation to matching rows/cells
- filters by module/category/project/program

Search should be server-side for large datasets.

# ============================================
# API DESIGN RULES
# ============================================

Laravel APIs must be clean and modular.

Use:
- controllers for HTTP handling
- services for business logic
- repositories/query classes where useful
- request validation classes
- resources/DTOs for API output
- policies for authorization
- jobs for heavy async tasks
- events for recalculation/update propagation

Do not put business logic directly inside controllers.
Do not duplicate calculation logic in Vue.

# ============================================
# TESTING REQUIREMENTS
# ============================================

Testing is important because Excel logic is complex.

Create tests for:
- formula reproduction
- calculation services
- dependency propagation
- imports
- exports
- permissions
- API endpoints
- database integrity

Critical calculations must be validated against known Excel results.

# ============================================
# SECURITY REQUIREMENTS
# ============================================

Implement:
- authentication
- authorization
- role-based permissions
- input validation
- secure file upload handling
- audit logging
- protection against unauthorized edits

Engineering data may be sensitive.

# ============================================
# INTERNATIONALIZATION
# ============================================

The application must be prepared for:
- French
- English

Use i18n architecture from the beginning.
Do not hardcode all labels directly in components.

# ============================================
# FUTURE AI BENCHMARKING LAYER
# ============================================

IMPORTANT:
The AI benchmarking layer is NOT the first development priority.

The platform must first be fully validated and stable.

Before AI implementation, the application must already support:
- correct business logic
- linked web pages/modules
- real-time or near-real-time updates
- editable data
- automatic calculations
- Excel import/export
- graph generation where required
- correct synchronization between modules
- reliable database structure
- good performance on enterprise hardware

Only after the core platform is finished and validated should the AI layer be added.

The future AI layer will be used for:
- benchmark analysis
- mass optimization suggestions
- competitor comparison
- anomaly detection
- detection of abnormal values
- identification of mass reduction opportunities
- intelligent recommendations
- portfolio scoring
- decision support for engineering teams
- historical comparison with previous projects
- optimization of vehicle mass data

The AI layer must use clean structured data from MySQL.
This is another reason why the database architecture must be designed properly from the beginning.

The AI layer must remain separated from the core calculation engine.

Core platform responsibilities:
- data management
- calculations
- synchronization
- exports
- collaboration
- visualization

AI layer responsibilities:
- recommendations
- prediction
- optimization
- benchmarking
- intelligent analysis

Do not tightly couple AI logic to the core business logic.
Design the architecture so AI can be added later without rewriting the whole application.

# ============================================
# DEVELOPMENT PRIORITIES
# ============================================

Priority order:

1. Excel logic analysis
2. Database schema design
3. Backend architecture
4. Server-side calculation engine
5. Dependency graph / cascading updates
6. Core editable modules
7. Performance optimization
8. Data integrity
9. Page/module synchronization
10. Excel import/export
11. Collaboration and permissions
12. Graph generation
13. User experience improvements
14. AI benchmarking layer

Do not start with AI.
Do not start with visual polish.
Do not start by cloning Excel visually before understanding the logic.

# ============================================
# FINAL SUCCESS METRIC
# ============================================

The project succeeds if:
- Excel is replaced sustainably
- the application is fast on enterprise machines
- the browser is never overloaded
- pages/modules are linked through the backend and database
- calculations cascade correctly
- data remains consistent
- exports match original Excel formats
- users can edit data safely
- collaboration is possible
- future AI benchmarking can be added cleanly

The final goal is a high-performance industrial web platform capable of replacing the Excel workflow, centralizing vehicle mass data, generating official deliverables, and later assisting engineering teams through AI-powered benchmark and optimization features.

# ============================================
# END OF .CURSORRULES
